<i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/urakuraku.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Rakuraku</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(9/1/02 3:35 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=923.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Difference between Hirigana and Kanji?</span><hr size=1>  The general rule is to use kanji if it is in the 1945 jyouyou kanji list, and hiragana otherwise. It's not set in stone though, this rule is frequently broken. Also, not all words are contained in a single kanji, many are composed of 2 or more kanji. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/usuryana.showPublicProfile?language=EN>suryana</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Fresh Meat</span><br> <font color=#336699>(9/1/02 9:37 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=923.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re:</span><hr size=1> Generally kanji alone will at least express some term or meaning, while hiragana only focus on how to pronounce.<br>
*Kanji is imported from chinese strokes (some are modified and some are still the same) but they read it as japanese.<br>
Japanese children should learn from hiragana first then proceed to kanji.  Normally we can notice that in most of the anime title, they put hiragana on the top of every kanji, in order to guide people who cannot read it. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/usuryana.showPublicProfile?language=EN>suryana</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Pre-Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(9/1/02 9:40 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=923.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re:</span><hr size=1> Generally kanji alone will at least express some term or meaning, while hiragana only focus on how to pronounce.<br>
*Kanji is imported from chinese strokes (some are modified and some are still the same) but they read it as japanese.<br>
Japanese children should learn from hiragana first then proceed to kanji.  Normally we can notice that in most of the anime title, they put hiragana on the top of every kanji, in order to guide people who cannot read it.<br>
To form a complete sentence, both kanji and hiragana are required. But for beginner or children, using hiragana only is okay. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/uflameraven.showPublicProfile?language=EN>FlameRaven</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(9/7/02 2:19 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=923.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Re:</span><hr size=1> Then when do you use katakana and when do you use hiragana? You could use either set of characters for words, correct? But when would you use katakana? I know for foreign words, but I've seen things that are developed in Japan...for example in Digimon during the 'digivolution' scenes, they have the american name of the digimon and then it's also written in katakana...I'm just a little confused... <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/ulacos.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Lacos</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(9/8/02 12:42 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=923.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Re:</span><hr size=1> You could think it so that when the word (an artificial Digimon name in this case) doesn't really mean anything, you use katakana. This isn't really a rule, but it'll give you a general view.<br>
Also, for your casual written Japanese, katakana could also be used to give emphasis on a word, like it's done in various manga. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/usuryana.showPublicProfile?language=EN>suryana</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Pre-Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(9/10/02 10:34 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=923.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Re: Re:</span><hr size=1> In this case, digimon is a short form of &quot;digital monsters&quot;, which means that it is imported word from English. <br>
Katakana is used to write imported words as we know but most probably for all foreign names as well (example: Batman, they write it as batoman).<br>
Another example is grey color.  They can either call it as:<br>
hai iro (hiragana) or<br>
gure (katakana)<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/udemondavies.showPublicProfile?language=EN>DemonDavies</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Pre-Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(9/13/02 2:42 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=923.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> ...</span><hr size=1> As people have said Katakana is generally used for foreign or imported words that the Japanese use in daily life. Kanji can be used as words or the same as the kanas for pronounciation.<br>
Hiragana is mostly used for scentence structure and kanji is used and Hiragana is ommited when nescessary.<br>
<br>
Using Katakana is just like using a normal word, you use it when you need it. In the case of Kanji, scentences can be made entirely out of Hiragana and Katakana and kanji can be left out. <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table><table border=0 width=95%><tr><td align=left valign="top"> </td><td align=right valign="top"><a href="http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.showPrevMessage?topicID=923.topic"> << Prev Topic</a>&nbsp;| <a href="http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.showNextMessage?topicID=923.topic"> Next Topic >> </a><br><br><a self href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=923.topic&index=7><img src=http://www.polykarbon.com/bbsimage/addreply.gif border=0 alt="Add Reply"></a> </td></tr></table><br><table width=95% border=0><td valign="top"> <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.emailToFriend?topicID=923.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/image/email.gif border=0 alt="Email This To a Friend"> Email This To a Friend</a><br> <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.threadControl?topicID=923.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/themes/professional/deleteThread.gif border=0 alt="Topic Control Image"> Topic Commands</a><br> <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.subscribeUnregisteredToTopic?topicID=923.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/themes/ultimate/subscribe.gif width=20 height=20 border=0 alt="Click to receive email notification of replies"> Click to receive email notification of replies</a> <br>  <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.unsubscribeUnregisteredToTopic?topicID=923.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/themes/ultimate/unsubscribe.gif width=20 height=20 border=0 alt="Click to stop receiving email notification of replies"> Click to stop receiving email notification of replies</a> <br> </td><td align="right" valign="top"></td></tr><tr align="right"><td colspan=2><form action=http://pub25.ezboard.com/B